00:50:00,865 --> 00:50:02,505
Obviously, this isn't about one person.

430
00:50:03,246 --> 00:50:06,087
The prior assistant finance director is similar.

431
00:50:06,507 --> 00:50:13,331
I have no questions that he will go places.

432
00:50:13,431 --> 00:50:14,672
And he's doing a lot of,

433
00:50:16,717 --> 00:50:20,259
things on the state level himself, he's already taken different positions on the state level.

434
00:50:21,480 --> 00:50:38,168
So just to say that, you know, we have, we also are trying very hard to hire the best and sometimes the best, there's no headroom, there's no growth room for them in terms of like, you know, a position between or, you know, sometimes even a director position.

435
00:50:38,228 --> 00:50:40,750
So we also have to recognize that as well as the only context.

436
00:50:41,230 --> 00:50:41,450
Thank you.

437
00:50:46,245 --> 00:50:46,926
Thank you for that.

438
00:50:46,946 --> 00:50:47,726
I appreciate that.

439
00:50:48,928 --> 00:51:00,439
Do we have any other questions for the finance and procurement budget?

440
00:51:05,804 --> 00:51:06,144
All right.

441
00:51:07,635 --> 00:51:16,080
One other note just to the chief of staff, if you could share with us the results of the classification and compensation study, that would be helpful.

442
00:51:16,680 --> 00:51:19,702
I know that we're expecting potentially some papers about that.

443
00:51:19,762 --> 00:51:28,467
So maybe a document or a presentation or both, I think would be helpful for us since these questions that come up a lot.

444
00:51:29,188 --> 00:51:29,548
Thank you.

445
00:51:33,910 --> 00:51:36,552
All right, we'll move to the last budget of the night.

446
00:51:37,778 --> 00:51:39,998
We have our information technology budget.

447
00:51:40,498 --> 00:51:45,419
We have Rich Lane, the city's IT director with us.

448
00:51:46,600 --> 00:52:05,323
Rich, if you could share the changes in your budget, what's changing, give us an explanation of them, and then give us a little update on what you've been up to this past year and what are some plans for upcoming years and potentially some items that we're not seeing funded here that you'd like to see funded in the future.

449
00:52:07,258 --> 00:52:07,658
Sounds great.

450
00:52:08,199 --> 00:52:12,626
I think the big thing, you know, budget again level funded as best we can.

451
00:52:12,646 --> 00:52:16,112
It does look like there's a couple of increases in so explain those first.

452
00:52:18,649 --> 00:52:28,500
Three of the big ticket items up till now have been funded through federal funds that as we all know expire 1231 this year.

453
00:52:29,501 --> 00:52:36,428
So these numbers, I don't know if you see page two of the spreadsheet or not, but basically it's

454
00:52:37,149 --> 00:52:51,437
adding in six months, so now I'll have to carry from January 1st to June 30th of next year, should be six months of the next year, of the last six months of this budget cycle, or whatever you want to call it.

455
00:52:52,117 --> 00:53:02,763
So I'm absorbing costs for our support help desk, TOS, for six months, Office 365 licensing for six months, and then our cybersecurity products.

456
00:53:03,363 --> 00:53:16,593
for six months, and that's where you see the addition of the 70,000 professional services for TOS and the combined 95,000 increase in computer applications for Office 365 and cybersecurity stuff.

457
00:53:17,154 --> 00:53:23,298
But other than that, if you take that out of the picture, everything's basically level funded from what it was last year.

458
00:53:26,381 --> 00:53:27,641
Is that math math for you, Zach?

459
00:53:28,762 --> 00:53:32,065
That looks like the numbers add up there, sure.

460
00:53:33,311 --> 00:53:43,022
Yeah, if you could share a little bit more about what you've been up to and what your plans are and other items that might need to be funded in the future.

461
00:53:43,595 --> 00:53:44,555
Sure.

462
00:53:45,175 --> 00:53:47,256
Basically, we're working still on infrastructure stuff.

463
00:53:47,356 --> 00:53:51,376
We have 25 plus years of technical debt.

464
00:53:51,396 --> 00:53:52,657
We're still trying to get out from under.

465
00:53:52,717 --> 00:53:54,497
We're making progress all the time.

466
00:53:55,217 --> 00:53:57,117
The hardest part is the foundational work.

467
00:53:57,417 --> 00:53:58,238
It takes the longest.

468
00:53:58,298 --> 00:54:02,478
It seems like you never move forward, but we're really close on a couple of big projects.

469
00:54:02,978 --> 00:54:05,959
Entirely new network for City Hall.

470
00:54:06,499 --> 00:54:07,859
That's going to be turned on pretty soon.

471
00:54:08,099 --> 00:54:10,640
Actually, it's already running in parallel to the old stuff.

472
00:54:10,700 --> 00:54:11,640
We're testing.

473
00:54:12,876 --> 00:54:22,684
And then the fiber network for the city in general, from all the municipal buildings, that's basically in place and being tested as we speak.

474
00:54:22,744 --> 00:54:24,365
I've got some more infrastructure work to do.

475
00:54:24,845 --> 00:54:28,909
The small data center we have, I'm testing that this week.

476
00:54:29,009 --> 00:54:38,055
I have my fiber guys coming tomorrow to finish one last piece of fiber inside of a building, and then we'll start moving across rapidly.

477
00:54:39,158 --> 00:54:44,501
Once that is done, then we can begin centralizing things.

478
00:54:44,681 --> 00:54:47,583
And this is where you really get a lot of cost savings.

479
00:54:48,043 --> 00:54:50,945
For instance, security systems, right?

480
00:54:51,025 --> 00:54:52,806
Every building has its own today.

481
00:54:52,846 --> 00:54:53,827
They're all really old.

482
00:54:53,847 --> 00:54:55,328
I just need to start updating some of them.

483
00:54:56,749 --> 00:54:58,029
I can centralize all that.

484
00:54:58,209 --> 00:55:05,214
And then you're just putting sort of the endpoints out in a building, like cameras or what have you, or gate card readers.

485
00:55:06,094 --> 00:55:09,376
where in the past you'd have to buy the whole surrounding infrastructure for that.

486
00:55:09,396 --> 00:55:13,378
There's a box that goes on the wall, the cabling, the readers, it gets expensive.

487
00:55:13,418 --> 00:55:15,639
And then just the recorders themselves are super expensive.

488
00:55:16,099 --> 00:55:23,102
So I can get away with doing one centralized for almost all of it and just point what little endpoints I need at whatever locations we're doing there.

489
00:55:25,175 --> 00:55:28,658
I think we have some server refreshes we have to think about.

490
00:55:29,479 --> 00:55:31,401
We're still going to be on admins for a while.

491
00:55:31,421 --> 00:55:34,624
That server is really much end of life.

492
00:55:35,304 --> 00:55:39,228
And so is the Softwrite server, which is our treasury server, where we collect all the money.

493
00:55:40,222 --> 00:55:42,905
So we have to figure out how we're going to move those forward.

494
00:55:43,906 --> 00:55:46,449
I'd like to do some other servers going away.

495
00:55:46,469 --> 00:55:51,053
I'd like to collapse down as many applications as I can into a very small virtual environment.

496
00:55:51,113 --> 00:55:56,378
That'll save a lot of money by doing it that way, as some of those other applications will go away down the road.

497
00:55:57,719 --> 00:56:04,283
So, and then Nina's favorite subject to always ask me about is new phones for City Hall.

498
00:56:05,323 --> 00:56:07,924
Hopefully going to happen in these sooner rather than later.

499
00:56:08,465 --> 00:56:11,606
Every other department outside of City Hall is on them.

500
00:56:12,927 --> 00:56:14,088
They're no problems.

501
00:56:14,128 --> 00:56:16,749
They're all enjoying the capabilities and features.

502
00:56:16,769 --> 00:56:19,390
It's been really great.

503
00:56:19,430 --> 00:56:20,591
We've ironed out a lot

504
00:56:21,715 --> 00:56:27,716
of the transition issues because of the age of our systems by doing the other buildings and other departments first.

505
00:56:28,236 --> 00:56:31,577
So when we go to do City Hall, it should be pretty uneventful, hopefully.

506
00:56:32,777 --> 00:56:43,160
But other than that, we just work on the usual stuff, policies and procedures, just try to formalize some things for the everyday so that when we get new hires, we can just hand them in the handbook.

507
00:56:43,660 --> 00:56:45,460
This is how you interact with technology.

508
00:56:45,520 --> 00:56:46,160
How do we use it?

509
00:56:46,200 --> 00:56:47,180
What do we expect from you?

510
00:56:48,141 --> 00:56:49,741
So our security and things like that.

511
00:56:51,344 --> 00:56:53,886
But that's all the back-end boring stuff.

512
00:56:54,386 --> 00:57:06,612
As far as funding future projects, the way my budget works now is that being a one-person shop, you can only take on so many products and whatever you want.

513
00:57:06,832 --> 00:57:10,774
If you ask any department head, they go up there and they're going to say, yes, I have 10 more projects I can do.

514
00:57:10,854 --> 00:57:15,696
But you have to be pragmatic about these things and say, how much can I get done in one fiscal year?

515
00:57:16,016 --> 00:57:18,457
Because some of these products have long time frames.

516
00:57:19,818 --> 00:57:22,539
the bigger project maybe cross across two fiscal years.

517
00:57:24,100 --> 00:57:28,662
I feel like I have the money to do what I want barring something catastrophic happening.

518
00:57:30,383 --> 00:57:32,724
But I do have a lot of products built in there.

519
00:57:32,764 --> 00:57:40,787
I just don't see myself need to come to you guys for stabilization funding or just my products aren't that big ticket item anymore.

520
00:57:44,869 --> 00:57:45,309
Thank you.

521
00:57:45,329 --> 00:57:46,430
I will go to Councilor Lemming.

522
00:57:48,282 --> 00:57:55,228
Thank you and thank you for keeping the entirety of the city's IT on your back.

523
00:57:57,309 --> 00:58:02,754
It is really miraculous how you're able to do to do this job as a one man department.

524
00:58:02,794 --> 00:58:04,195
So very much appreciated.

525
00:58:04,735 --> 00:58:18,207
I would like to ask is sort of what's this what's the status of the phishing emails within within the city because I get.

526
00:58:19,607 --> 00:58:30,294
I get a good amount of emails from Isaac Bears asking for a five-minute meeting, and it's not actually from him.

527
00:58:30,314 --> 00:58:33,076
He never sends me the gift card.

528
00:58:33,196 --> 00:58:34,017
He never sends it.

529
00:58:34,157 --> 00:58:34,637
I don't know why.

530
00:58:36,760 --> 00:58:42,263
It's always, I'm rushing to a meeting, do you have five minutes to talk, just reply to this email kind of things.

531
00:58:42,483 --> 00:58:58,191
And it concerns me, not because I've ever tried to respond to those, but reading about the case, I think it was in Arlington where they lost quite a bit of money because somebody fell for one of those things.

532
00:58:59,452 --> 00:59:12,682
So I'm just wondering if your finger is on the pulse of that issue and if there have been any incidents that have been memorable around City Hall where some employees might've fallen for that.

533
00:59:13,423 --> 00:59:14,183
No, we're pretty good.

534
00:59:14,203 --> 00:59:19,487
I mean, I talk to the employees all the time about it and have them trained up pretty well on how to spot them.

535
00:59:20,728 --> 00:59:25,592
And if they have any questions, they'll just send it right to me and say, is this really from whomever?

536
00:59:26,389 --> 00:59:28,890
And I'll go down and just point out all the flaws in it.

537
00:59:29,270 --> 00:59:30,271
And they usually catch on.

538
00:59:30,411 --> 00:59:42,476
And we haven't had any incidents that 99% of the time or 90% of the incidents that happen out there aren't from a phishing email or somebody clicking on a link they shouldn't have.

539
00:59:42,496 --> 00:59:45,497
They're from somebody calling and pretending to be someone else.

540
00:59:45,577 --> 00:59:46,858
Social engineering, it's called.

541
00:59:48,198 --> 00:59:49,439
That's what happened to Arlington.

542
00:59:50,359 --> 00:59:51,720
Not to reveal too much, but

543
00:59:53,252 --> 00:59:55,978
It wasn't because of an email or anything like that.

544
00:59:57,213 --> 00:59:58,314
things that went on there.

545
00:59:59,474 --> 01:00:09,160
I took the lessons learned from that and went to the people of the department here, the corollary department explains to them what happened, what they should look for and what have you.

546
01:00:09,180 --> 01:00:12,202
So it won't happen here, that type of thing.

547
01:00:12,262 --> 01:00:14,143
But yeah, it's the same thing.

548
01:00:14,203 --> 01:00:18,165
I get so much spam, it's ridiculous, but then it ebbs and flows.

549
01:00:18,185 --> 01:00:20,987
And as soon as you shut off one avenue, they pick up another one.

550
01:00:21,467 --> 01:00:23,088
This is all robotic, right?

551
01:00:23,148 --> 01:00:24,709
It's all just automation that they're creating.

552
01:00:25,249 --> 01:00:33,471
hundreds of thousands of fake email addresses a day and just scraping the website, seeing all the names of the people, your treasurer, your Judy Johnson.

553
01:00:33,491 --> 01:00:37,672
I'm going to send Judy Johnson a very official looking thing.

554
01:00:37,732 --> 01:00:40,213
Here's the invoice you're looking for or what have you.

555
01:00:40,233 --> 01:00:46,914
If she's doing a hundred things in a day like she usually is, maybe it gets through when she clicks on the PDF or what have you.

556
01:00:46,954 --> 01:00:48,335
That's what they're banking on.

557
01:00:48,355 --> 01:00:51,915
It's this mass mailing type of thing that goes on.

558
01:00:55,767 --> 01:01:03,412
The biggest people they are caught up by, it's usually schools and police departments, to be honest with you.

559
01:01:03,812 --> 01:01:04,353
I don't think.

560
01:01:05,033 --> 01:01:15,199
anyone finds, you know, the veteran services office that interested, they're going to have a coordinated campaign against them in particular type of thing.

561
01:01:15,299 --> 01:01:27,507
So what they're going for is either locking you out of everything and then ransomware, obviously, or just something that makes the news that that raises their name up there further in the hacker community.

562
01:01:28,350 --> 01:01:29,691
But no, we do a really good job.

563
01:01:29,711 --> 01:01:30,571
We've had trainings.

564
01:01:32,052 --> 01:01:35,273
I have good faith in people doing the right thing.

565
01:01:35,313 --> 01:01:39,014
I just had somebody send me one today that was actually laughing about it.

566
01:01:39,074 --> 01:01:46,477
Now, and somebody that isn't the most sophisticated computer user, but since I've shown them how to spot them, they actually, it's like a little game for them.

567
01:01:46,917 --> 01:01:50,319
You know, they send them on and we just have it blacklisted, but it's almost meaningless.

568
01:01:51,179 --> 01:01:55,281
We do have a pretty good spam slash phishing email.

569
01:01:56,469 --> 01:02:00,931
Filter on the front end before emails even hit inboxes, does a pretty good job.

570
01:02:00,951 --> 01:02:07,334
But again, they're as fast as we tweak that, they're tweaking in a different direction and getting through in some instances.

571
01:02:07,374 --> 01:02:15,017
But if you saw the numbers of emails that never made it to desktops, it's the numbers that make it are minuscule out of the total.

572
01:02:15,037 --> 01:02:21,100
All right, I'll go to Councilor Sang.

573
01:02:22,771 --> 01:02:23,391
Hi there, Rich.

574
01:02:24,472 --> 01:02:33,095
You mentioned that we're backfilling a lot of things that used to be funded with federal funds with grants.

575
01:02:33,695 --> 01:02:40,298
I'm curious as to what grants we are already taking advantage of.

576
01:02:40,438 --> 01:02:51,762
Are there any out there that we haven't applied for yet that we could apply for to help with funding these programs and funding maybe future programming?

577
01:02:52,703 --> 01:02:56,004
Yeah, so maybe I should have been a little more detailed.

578
01:02:56,304 --> 01:02:59,826
The money that I was talking about as far as my budget was ARPA money that fell off.

579
01:03:00,166 --> 01:03:01,567
So that's a one-time thing.

580
01:03:01,607 --> 01:03:03,507
It's not like a grant you can apply for.

581
01:03:03,527 --> 01:03:04,488
Obviously, that's gone away.

582
01:03:05,448 --> 01:03:06,228
We did get a grant.

583
01:03:06,268 --> 01:03:09,210
We got the municipal fiber grant that the state offers.

584
01:03:09,730 --> 01:03:11,050
You can get that every two years.

585
01:03:11,911 --> 01:03:19,774
That paid for about half of the fiber product itself, maybe a little under half of it, which was a huge win for us.

586
01:03:21,157 --> 01:03:32,009
There's another one, it's called the, boy, I think it's just like the Community Compact IT Grant or something, IT Infrastructure Grant, I think it's IT Infrastructure Grant.

587
01:03:32,609 --> 01:03:36,073
We can apply for that, that opens in January or so.

588
01:03:36,093 --> 01:03:37,434
I think that's about up to 250K.

589
01:03:37,454 --> 01:03:39,236
So just waiting to see what,

590
01:03:43,443 --> 01:03:48,487
I don't want to spend it on a $40,000 project, right, that we get the grant and only spend it on something big.

591
01:03:48,547 --> 01:03:53,070
Now that's what we end up with, and of course we'll apply and get the money every little bit helps.

592
01:03:54,010 --> 01:03:59,614
But if we need to tie it into what we're doing on the finance side somehow or

593
01:04:00,935 --> 01:04:07,841
On the side of some other system that needs to get replaced, or bringing in a new system for automation or for something along those lines.

594
01:04:08,281 --> 01:04:16,047
So we'll see as the year goes on, I talk to people all the time about what their needs are going forward, what they're thinking about as far as modernization.

595
01:04:16,608 --> 01:04:19,350
And then there's some cyber security grants too.

596
01:04:20,930 --> 01:04:29,133
The problem with them are is that they're not, they're not well written as far as the contracts and the products they chose at the state level.

597
01:04:29,713 --> 01:04:31,814
So it really locks you into one path.

598
01:04:32,794 --> 01:04:38,156
So in looking through them, I was just like, you know, it's actually going to cost us more money in the long run to

599
01:04:39,907 --> 01:04:45,469
replace what we have, the state pays like two years of it, and then you have to go back out on your own.

600
01:04:45,489 --> 01:04:47,690
So you have to migrate back again to something else.

601
01:04:47,710 --> 01:04:53,953
So the acquisition and renewal costs outweigh any advantages and really get some of those.

602
01:04:54,673 --> 01:04:55,674
But we're always listening.

603
01:04:55,694 --> 01:04:58,015
I talk to all my peers in the surrounding areas.

604
01:04:58,095 --> 01:05:01,176
If they hear of anything, I'll share the knowledge.

605
01:05:08,079 --> 01:05:08,319
Thanks.

606
01:05:10,170 --> 01:05:10,851
Thank you, Rich.

607
01:05:11,611 --> 01:05:13,913
Just had a couple last questions.

608
01:05:14,013 --> 01:05:16,415
I noticed that telephone is zeroed out.

609
01:05:16,495 --> 01:05:18,056
Is that moving to the facilities budget?

610
01:05:19,117 --> 01:05:21,999
No, it's so it is a really old legacy account.

611
01:05:22,039 --> 01:05:25,801
Like we haven't had copper phones in over 13 years.

612
01:05:26,562 --> 01:05:28,163
It was an old account for that.

613
01:05:28,183 --> 01:05:30,625
You know, fax lines, things like that.

614
01:05:31,145 --> 01:05:35,388
I was using it just to pay for stuff like BIOS Internet for buildings and things.

615
01:05:35,428 --> 01:05:35,769
But it's like

616
01:05:36,636 --> 01:05:41,417
Every year, I'd have to add more money to it from somewhere else because it's only at a 7,000 cap.

617
01:05:41,517 --> 01:05:54,040
I was like, well, instead of extending it, I'll just roll it into, I think, put it in computer software or something and just deal with it that way, just save less paperwork for everyone.

618
01:05:55,561 --> 01:05:55,821
Got it.

619
01:05:58,230 --> 01:06:07,093
I know that with this rollover, about $170,000 for six months, so probably looking at $340,000, $350,000 for a full year.

620
01:06:07,573 --> 01:06:11,314
So we're going to see the rest of that in the next fiscal year budget.

621
01:06:12,035 --> 01:06:16,996
And is there any expectation of, I guess, are these good deals?

622
01:06:17,016 --> 01:06:18,777
Is there any way we could address that cost?

623
01:06:24,917 --> 01:06:30,424
If you want to have email, say you want to have Office apps, Microsoft Office apps.

624
01:06:30,444 --> 01:06:32,206
Make a lot of people happy for a week.

625
01:06:32,967 --> 01:06:33,347
Yeah.

626
01:06:34,489 --> 01:06:35,930
Make me very happy, I'll tell you that.

627
01:06:37,930 --> 01:06:40,052
Someone said to me, well, did you see my email?

628
01:06:40,072 --> 01:06:40,812
I'm like, no, I haven't.

629
01:06:40,832 --> 01:06:42,373
It's like, well, you got to read my email.

630
01:06:42,393 --> 01:06:46,256
I'm like, well, if you needed an immediate answer, why'd you use such a slow mode of communication?

631
01:06:47,717 --> 01:06:50,079
But yeah, so there's not much you can do.

632
01:06:50,119 --> 01:06:51,741
We're holding Microsoft, right?

633
01:06:51,781 --> 01:06:54,503
They're announcing new pricing in July.

634
01:06:54,523 --> 01:06:59,586
So we're all kind of sitting and waiting how much they're going to get us for this time.

635
01:07:01,228 --> 01:07:03,229
The same thing for our cybersecurity products.

636
01:07:03,529 --> 01:07:06,030
They don't go up a lot year-to-year, which is good.

637
01:07:07,151 --> 01:07:12,314
Fortunately, we go through a reseller, which buys them in bulk, so they can really press the pricing.

638
01:07:13,535 --> 01:07:16,076
They can walk away to a different vendor if they don't like it.

639
01:07:16,096 --> 01:07:17,537
There's not much you can do.

640
01:07:17,597 --> 01:07:19,358
The only thing you can do is go to Google Suite.

641
01:07:20,268 --> 01:07:21,429
or your Microsoft Office.

642
